value.value: Adult prothoracic muscle that attaches to a broad region of the medial sternal apodeme and tapers to insert on the posterior edge of the coxa cuticle (Rivlin et al., 2004; Azevedo et al., 2024). It is composed of 3-4 fibers (Rivlin et al., 2004). It moves the coxa medially (Azevedo et al., 2024).
Any adult leg muscle (FBbt:00053096) that is part of some prothoracic segment (FBbt:00000017).
Any leg depressor muscle (FBbt:00058842) that is part of some prothoracic segment (FBbt:00000017).

Adult prothoracic muscle that depresses (extends) the trochanter and has its origin outside of the coxa (Miller, 1950; Azevedo et al., 2024). There are two of these on each side, one that originates on the tergum and one that originates on the sternum (Azevedo et al., 2024). Its fibers insert on the prothoracic trochanter extensor (extracoxal trochanter depressor) tendon (Azevedo et al., 2024).

Depressor muscle of the adult prothoracic trochanter that extends along the medial coxa, ventral to the extracoxal trochanter depressor muscle 34 (Miller, 1950). It extends the coxa-trochanter joint (Azevedo et al., 2024).
Depressor muscle of the adult prothoracic tibia that extends along the medial femur, proximal to the tibial depressor muscle 41.
Any accessory tibial flexor muscle (FBbt:00059104) that is part of some prothoracic segment (FBbt:00000017).
Depressor muscle of the adult prothoracic tarsus that extends along the tibia, medial to the tarsal levator muscle 42. It is composed of 20 to 24 fibers (Soler et al., 2004).
Any leg levator muscle (FBbt:00058848) that is part of some prothoracic segment (FBbt:00000017).
Levator muscle of the adult prothoracic trochanter that extends along the lateral coxa and is lateral to the mesal levator muscle 37.

definition.value: Azevedo et al. (2024) find only one (main) prothoracic intracoxal trochanter levator (flexor) muscle, but this is split into dorsal and ventral regions attaching on different sides of the tendon, innervated by different MNs. The 'dorsal' fibers probably correspond to this 'lateral' muscle.

value.value: Levator muscle of the adult prothoracic trochanter that extends along the medial coxa and is medial to the lateral levator muscle 36.

definition.value: Azevedo et al. (2024) find only one (main) prothoracic intracoxal trochanter levator (flexor) muscle, but this is split into dorsal and ventral regions attaching on different sides of the tendon, innervated by different MNs. The 'ventral' fibers probably correspond to this 'mesal' muscle.

value.value: Levator muscle of the adult prothoracic tibia that extends along the lateral femur.
Levator muscle of the adult prothoracic tarsus that extends in the distal tibia, lateral to the tarsal depressor muscle 43.
Any leg reductor muscle (FBbt:00058854) that is part of some prothoracic segment (FBbt:00000017).
Reductor muscle of the adult prothoracic femur that extends along the trochanter.
Somatic muscle that is part of the mesothorax.

Muscle involved in the mechanism of flight. The indirect flight muscles are involved in the deformation of the thoracic terga that bear the wings but are not directly attached to the wing, whereas the direct flight muscles are attached directly to the wing and aid in fine control of its movement. These muscles derive from adepithelial cells associated with the wing disc (Sudarsan et al., 2001; Kozopas and Nusse, 2002).
Muscle involved in flight that is not directly attached to the wing base. It derives from an indirect flight muscle precursor cell of the wing disc (Sudarsan et al., 2001).

Indirect flight muscle that extends anterioposteriorly, along the full length of the thorax (Dickinson and Tu, 1997). There are six of these muscles on each side, each with a single muscle cell (Dickinson and Tu, 1997). They have anterior attachment sites across the anterior and dorsal tergum and posterior attachment sites in the postnotum (Miyan and Ewing 1985). It functions to depress the wings by longitudinal arching of the scutum (Miller, 1950).

definition.value: DLM1-6 numbered ventral to dorsal (see Ikeda and Koenig (1988) - FBrf0048552), muscles 45a-f numbered dorsal to ventral (see Tanouye and Wyman (1981) - FBrf0074584).

value.value: The most dorsal and shortest of the dorsal longitudinal indirect flight muscles. It is innervated by the indirect flight muscle motor neuron MN5.
The second most dorsal of the dorsal longitudinal indirect flight muscles. It is innervated by the indirect flight muscle motor neuron MN5.
The third most dorsal of the dorsal longitudinal indirect flight muscles. It is innervated by the indirect flight muscle motor neuron MN4.
The fourth most dorsal of the dorsal longitudinal indirect flight muscles. It is innervated by the indirect flight muscle motor neuron MN3.
The second most ventral of the dorsal longitudinal indirect flight muscles. It is innervated by the indirect flight muscle motor neuron MN2.
The most ventral of the dorsal longitudinal indirect flight muscles. It is innervated by the indirect flight muscle motor neuron MN1.
An indirect flight muscle that functions as a wing elevator. It extends from the has a dorsal attachment site in the posterior notum and a ventral attachment to the postnotum.
The most anterior of the lateral oblique dorsal muscles.
The most posterior of the lateral oblique dorsal muscles.
An indirect flight muscle that functions as a wing elevator. It has a dorsal attachment to the anterior notum and a ventral attachment to the mesothoracic preepisternum, anterior to the coxa.
The most anterior of the tergosternal muscles.
One of the posterior tergosternal muscles, dorsal to the tergosternal muscle 47c in the notum.
One of the posterior tergosternal muscles, ventral to the tergosternal muscle 47b in the notum.

An indirect flight muscle that functions as a wing elevator. It has a dorsal attachment site in the mid notum and a ventral attachment site in the metathoracic preepisternum, dorsoanterior to the coxa. It is posterior to the tergosternal and anterior to the lateral oblique dorsal muscles. It is innervated by the adult fruitless vMS2 neuron.
The anterior of the lateral oblique dorsal muscles.
The posterior of the lateral oblique dorsal muscles.

Relatively small muscle that inserts directly on a sclerite of the wing hinge to allow for the fine control of wing positioning for behaviors such as flight, grooming or courtship (Dickinson and Tu, 1997). There are thirteen of these muscles on each side (Dickinson and Tu, 1997). It is derived from a direct flight muscle precursor cell of the wing disc (Kozopas and Nusse, 2002).

Direct flight muscle extending from the anterior notum to the basalar of the wing (Sink, 2006). It serves to draw the wing horizontally forwards (Miller, 1950). It is innervated by the b1 motor neuron.
Direct flight muscle extending from the notum to the posterior of the basalar. Together with flight muscle b1, it functions to extend the wing (Sink, 2006).
Anterior-most of a pair of direct flight muscles that function to depress the anal portion of the wing (Miller, 1950).
Posterior-most of a pair of direct flight muscles that function to depress the anal portion of the wing (Miller, 1950).

Muscle of the epipleural muscle group, which is involved in extending the wing and pulling the anterior wing margin down, thereby pronating the wing (Sink, 2006). It is innervated by a fruitless vMS2 neuron.
Direct flight muscle that depresses the anterior border of the wing (Miller, 1950). It is innervated by the b2 motor neuron.

Indirect flight muscle that originates broadly over the dorsal episternum and inserts via a thick tendon on the meso-scutum (Dickinson and Tu, 1997). This muscle is innervated by the dorsal and ventral tp motor neurons.

definition.value: Classified as indirect in Dickinson and Tu (1997), as these muscles do not connect to a wing sclerite, but they note that the muscles do insert within the hinge region and could affect hinge mechanics.

value.value: Direct flight muscle that inserts at one of the wing axillary sclerites (Sink, 2006).

Direct flight muscle connected to the anterior of the first axillary sclerite that, together with muscle I2, serves to raise the wing and draw it backwards (Miller, 1950). It is innervated by the I1 motor neuron.

Direct flight muscle connected to the anterior of the third axillary sclerite that, together with the posterior third axillary muscles, serves to depress the anal portion of the wing (Miller, 1950). It is innervated by the III1 motor neuron.

Direct flight muscle connected to the posterior of the third axillary sclerite that, together with muscle III1, serves to depress the anal portion of the wing (Miller, 1950). There are two of these muscles that form a dorsoventrally-oriented group, posterior to muscle III1 (Trimarchi and Schneiderman, 1994; Ehrhardt et al., 2023).
Direct flight muscle connected to the posterior of the first axillary sclerite that, together with muscle I1, serves to raise the wing and draw it backwards (Miller, 1950).
Direct flight muscle connecting to the subalar sclerite that serves to draw the wing backwards toward the body (Miller, 1950).

Indirect flight control muscle that is involved in generating tension in the thorax, controlling wing beat frequency (Dickinson and Tu, 1997). There are two of these muscles on each side and they originate on the mesofurca and insert on the ventral surface of the prealar apophysis (Dickinson and Tu, 1997).
